excerpt: Twin spires top this baroque-style 17th-century cathedral, with a museum housing sacred treasures.
detail_description: Salzburg Cathedral, with its twin spires and baroque-style architecture, is a monumental symbol of the city's religious significance and historical wealth. The cathedral houses a museum that displays sacred treasures, adding to its allure. The building has undergone several reconstructions over the centuries, with the current structure showcasing early Baroque ecclesiastical architecture at its finest. Visitors are captivated by the towering facade and turquoise domes of this 17th-century marvel.
name: Salzburg Cathedral

excerpt: Iconic, 17th-century palace with ornamental gardens, plus classical concerts in the lavish ballroom.
detail_description: Mirabell Palace, a 17th-century architectural gem located in Salzburg, is renowned for its ornamental gardens and opulent interior. The palace was featured in the iconic film 'The Sound of Music,' with its gardens serving as the backdrop for memorable scenes. Built by Archbishop Wolf Dietrich in 1606 and later redesigned in Baroque style, the palace boasts exquisite interior decorations including stucco and wall paintings.
name: Mirabell Palace

excerpt: Huge 11th-century fortress complex on a hilltop with views over city to the Alps, plus museums.
detail_description: Perched on a hilltop with commanding views of the city and the Alps, Fortress Hohensalzburg is an impressive 11th-century complex that draws in over 1.4 million visitors annually. To avoid the crowds, it's best to arrive early and take a glass funicular or embark on a steep 20-minute walk up Festungsgasse in the Old Town to reach this iconic landmark.
name: Fortress Hohensalzburg

excerpt: Birthplace of Wolfgang Mozart in 1756, now a house museum with tours detailing his young life.
detail_description: Mozart's Birthplace, also known as Mozarts Geburtshaus, is a significant historical site in Salzburg. The yellow townhouse was where Wolfgang Mozart, one of the most influential composers in history, was born and lived for 17 years. Today, it operates as a house museum offering tours that provide insights into Mozart's early life. Visitors can explore three floors filled with personal belongings, musical instruments, family portraits, and other important items related to Mozart.
name: Mozart's Birthplace

excerpt: Catholic church & monastery dating to the 7th century, featuring a cemetery, catacombs & a museum.
detail_description: St. Peter's Abbey, situated in Salzburg, Austria, is a renowned Benedictine monastery and Catholic church with a rich history dating back to the 7th century. Established by Saint Rupert, it stands as one of the oldest abbey-church and monastery complexes in the German-speaking world. The Romanesque St. Peter's Church, built in 1143 and later restored with Baroque and Rococo elements, showcases ornate altarpieces by Martin Johann Schmidt.
name: St. Peter's Abbey

detail_description: Getreidegasse Street, the main shopping artery of Salzburg since Medieval times, is a must-visit for history and culture enthusiasts. It's home to Mozart's birthplace and features intricately decorated shop signs that harken back to a time when people couldn't read, using symbols to represent their trade. The street winds through beautiful baroque architecture and offers international shopping options alongside historic sites.
name: Getreidegasse Street

excerpt: Sumptuous 16th-century square centering on a baroque fountain, used for music & sporting events.
detail_description: Residenzplatz is a magnificent 16th-century square featuring a stunning baroque fountain and serving as the backdrop for various cultural events. It holds historical significance, being featured in famous films like The Sound of Music. Visitors can explore nearby attractions such as Mirabell Palace and Garden, Felsenreitschule, St. Peters cemetery, Schloss Leopoldskron, and Nonnberg Convent.
name: Residenzplatz

excerpt: Rocky plateau above Salzburg with woods, meadows, castles & a modern art museum, reached by a lift.
detail_description: Mönchsberg, also known as Monks Hill, is a rocky plateau above Salzburg offering stunning views of the old town and the Alps. This wooded ridge features meadows, castles, and a modern art museum that can be reached by a lift. The area is home to notable attractions such as the Benedictine Abbey of St. Peter with buildings dating back to the 17th and 18th centuries, including a church remodeled in Rococo style.
name: Mönchsberg

excerpt: Family-friendly zoo with animals from Africa, Eurasia, Australia & the Americas, plus dining.
detail_description: Salzburg Zoo Hellbrunn is a family-friendly destination featuring over 1,500 animals from various continents. Originally established in the 15th century as an archbishopric zoological park, it now showcases 150 different species. The zoo's unique topography, nestled next to a cliff leading to the large African savannah, adds to its charm.
name: Salzburg Zoo Hellbrunn

excerpt: Massive, interactive science & natural history museum, also offering an aquarium & reptile zoo.
detail_description: The Haus der Natur, also known as the Museum of Natural History and Technology, is a captivating science and natural history museum located in Salzburg, Austria. This expansive museum offers a wide range of interactive exhibits suitable for all ages. Visitors can explore permanent displays such as an aquarium and reptile zoo with over 35 tanks showcasing animals from around the world. Additionally, there's an interactive science center providing hands-on experiences to learn about various topics including energy and the human body.
name: Haus der Natur

excerpt: Panoramic city views feature from this scenic hill with a circa-1600s Capucines cloister & eatery.
detail_description: Kapuzinerberg is a picturesque hill in Salzburg offering stunning city views and featuring a Capucines cloister dating back to the 1600s. Visitors can enjoy a mix of nature and culture by hiking to Franziskischlossel, indulging in local cuisine, exploring churches and museums, and attending concerts. The area is also described as gay-friendly, with opportunities for biking adventures and positive feedback from the LGBT community.
name: Kapuzinerberg

excerpt: A UNESCO World Heritage Site, this expansive Baroque complex offers art & cultural history tours.
detail_description: The DomQuartier Salzburg is a UNESCO World Heritage Site that showcases the rich arts and cultural history of Salzburg. This expansive Baroque complex includes a cathedral, an Abbey, and five separate museums. One of the museums, the famous Dom Museum, houses the Kunst und Wunderkammer, which features a fascinating collection of stuffed animals, fossils, scientific devices, and rock crystal grinding works.
name: DomQuartier Salzburg

detail_description: Salzach River offers a variety of experiences for visitors to Salzburg. One option is to take a cruise along the river, with different tour lengths available, providing stunning views of the city and surrounding alps. Another way to enjoy the river is by taking a leisurely stroll along its banks, offering picturesque vistas and photo opportunities of the city skyline and Hohensalzburg fortress. The northern point near Mirabell Gardens provides an especially beautiful view at sunset or in the early morning.
name: Salzach

excerpt: Salzburg is an Austrian city on the border of Germany, with views of the Eastern Alps. The city is divided by the Salzach River, with medieval and baroque buildings of the pedestrian Altstadt (Old City) on its left bank, facing the 19th-century Neustadt (New City) on its right. The Altstadt birthplace of famed composer Mozart is preserved as a museum displaying his childhood instruments.
detail_description: Salzburg, an Austrian city near the German border, offers stunning views of the Eastern Alps. Divided by the Salzach River, it features a medieval Altstadt on one bank and a 19th-century Neustadt on the other. The birthplace of Mozart is now a museum showcasing his childhood instruments. Known for being the setting of The Sound Of Music, Salzburg is a must-see destination with guided tours to its filming locations.
name: Salzburg

excerpt: Spacious art museum featuring contemporary & 19th-century works by Salzburg artists.
detail_description: The Salzburg Museum, located in the New Residential Palace (Neue Residenz), is a spacious art museum showcasing contemporary and 19th-century works by local artists. Spanning 3,000 square meters, this museum offers immersive exhibitions that include Bronze Age salt mining artifacts, rare musical instruments from the 16th century, and The Salzburg Myth display exploring the city's Romantic Transfiguration.
name: Salzburg Museum

detail_description: Experience the enchanting Original Sound of Music Tour in Salzburg, a must-visit for families. This tour offers a nostalgic journey to the iconic filming locations of The Sound of Music. Delight in visiting spots like Mirabell Gardens, Leopoldskron Palace, Hellbrunn Palace, the picturesque Salzburg lake district, and the charming Mondsee church where Maria and Baron von Trapp exchanged vows.
name: The Original Sound of Music Tour Salzburg

excerpt: Futuristic building, home to the Flying Bulls display team, plus art shows, restaurants & bars.
detail_description: Red Bull Hangar-7 is a futuristic building located next to the main Salzburg Airport. It houses the Flying Bulls display team and features various aeronautical artifacts, including airplanes, motorbikes, rally cars, and Formula 1 exhibits. The hangar also boasts several bars, a cafe, and a Michelin Star restaurant. Its unique architecture with a hydrofoil dome makes it an exciting place to visit.
name: Red Bull Hangar-7

excerpt: Toy museum with hands-on exhibits & a children's cinema, plus antique toys, dolls & teddy bears.
detail_description: The Toy Museum Salzburg, also known as the Spielzeugmuseum, is a captivating attraction located near Mozartplatz and Mirabell Palace. It offers an enchanting experience for both kids and adults with its diverse collection of antique toys, dolls, and teddy bears. The museum is divided into two sections: one showcasing historical displays of old toys and games, while the other features interactive rides and activities like a marble run and a mini race-circuit.
name: Toy Museum Salzburg

excerpt: Busy Altstadt, the old town, centers on Getreidegasse, a narrow, pedestrian street with shops selling folk costumes and antiques. Mozart’s Birthplace has exhibits on the composer’s early life. The Domquartier includes the domed 1600s Salzburg Cathedral and the baroque Residence, with art by Rembrandt and Rubens. A steep path and a funicular lead to Hohensalzburg Fortress, with several museums and city views.
detail_description: Altstadt Salzburg, also known as the old town, is a bustling area filled with history and culture. Getreidegasse, a charming pedestrian street, is lined with shops selling traditional costumes and antiques. Visitors can explore Mozart's Birthplace to learn about the composer's early life or visit the Domquartier to see the stunning Salzburg Cathedral and baroque Residence featuring art by renowned artists.
name: Altstadt Salzburg

detail_description: The Viewpoint of Old Town in Salzburg is a UNESCO World Heritage site, featuring historical buildings with Medieval and Baroque architecture. It's a perfect place for leisurely walks, admiring the sights, enjoying coffee, and shopping. The area is home to major tourist attractions like Mozart's birthplace. Nearby districts like Elisabeth-Vorstadt offer convenient accommodation options while Lehen connects to the western edge of the Old Town.
name: Viewpoint of Old Town

excerpt: This large courtyard is best known for its memorial statue of composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
detail_description: Mozartplatz is a spacious courtyard located in the heart of Salzburg's Old Town, featuring a striking memorial statue of the renowned composer Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. The square is home to various museums and attractions, such as the Salzburg Museum, Traklhaus, and The Salzburg Christmas Museum. Additionally, adjacent squares like Residenplaz and Domplaz are easily accessible from Mozartplatz.
name: Mozartplatz

excerpt: Baroque-style museum with a courtyard, showcasing graphics & photographs by modern Austrian artists.
detail_description: Museum der Moderne Salzburg, located in the New Residential Palace (Neue Residenz), is a must-visit for art and cultural history enthusiasts. The museum showcases modern Austrian artists' graphics and photographs within its Baroque-style architecture. With 3,000 square meters of renovated space, visitors can immerse themselves in multimedia-enhanced exhibitions that range from Bronze Age artifacts to rare 16th-century musical instruments.
name: Museum der Moderne Salzburg

detail_description: Mozartplatz is a charming square in close proximity to Residenzplatz and the birthplace of Mozart. The focal point of this square is a statue of the legendary composer, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. It's definitely worth a visit for music enthusiasts and history buffs alike.
name: Mozartplatz

excerpt: This museum boasts a circular painting of Salzburg in 1829 that guests can see through telescopes.
detail_description: The Panorama Museum, situated near Mozart Square, features a remarkable 360-degree painting of Salzburg from the early 19th century. Created by Johann Michael Sattler, this circular artwork offers a glimpse into the city's appearance during Mozart's era. Visitors can use telescopes to observe intricate details of the historical scenery and architecture depicted in the painting. Additionally, the museum showcases supporting exhibits leading up to the main attraction, providing an engaging experience for guests.
name: Panorama Museum

excerpt: Picturesque cemetery with baroque tombs of nobility as well as 12th-century catacombs & chapels.
detail_description: Friedhof St. Peter, also known as Petersfriedhof, is a charming cemetery in Salzburg with a rich history dating back to before 700 AD. The graveyard is adorned with baroque tombs of nobility and features 12th-century catacombs and chapels carved into the rock face. Notable graves include those of Wolfgang's sister Nannerl and his childhood friend Michael Haydn. The cemetery, surrounded by the Church of St.
name: Friedhof St. Peter (Petersfriedhof)

excerpt: Benedictine monastery founded in the 8th century & a protected monument, with a church & a crypt.
detail_description: Stift Nonnberg is a historic Benedictine monastery and a protected monument, dating back to the 8th century. It was founded in 714 by St. Rupert, the patron saint of Salzburg. The abbey gained fame as the setting for the movie 'The Sound of Music,' where Maria joined before becoming a governess to the von Trapp family.
name: Stift Nonnberg

excerpt: Housed in Mozart's old home, this museum displays artifacts dedicated to the composer's life.
detail_description: The Mozart Residence, located on Makartplatz, is a museum housed in the former home of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. The residence was partially destroyed during World War II but was meticulously reconstructed and opened to the public as a museum in 1996. This eight-room apartment showcases original portraits, documents, and musical instruments from Mozart's life, including his fortepiano. Visitors can explore the history of the house and learn about Mozart's years in Salzburg and his family's life.
name: Mozart Residence

excerpt: Renaissance villa known for its landscaped gardens, trick water fountains & folklore museum.
detail_description: Schloss Hellbrunn is a Renaissance villa with beautifully landscaped gardens, famous for its trick water fountains and folklore museum. Built by Markus Sittikus von Hohenems in the early 17th century, this baroque palace was designed as a day residence without bedrooms. The estate is known for its 'Watergames,' where unsuspecting guests are squirted with water from hidden fountains.
name: Schloss Hellbrunn

excerpt: Casino in a Baroque castle-palace, with table games & slots, a restaurant & a smart dress code.
detail_description: Located in the stunning baroque palace of Schloss Klessheim, Casino Salzburg offers a luxurious gambling experience in Wals-Siezenheim, Austria. The casino boasts a 25,000 sq ft gaming area with an array of modern slot machines and live table games such as American Roulette, Blackjack, Macau Baccarat, and Poker. Additionally, visitors can enjoy open-air games on the terrace overlooking the beautiful English garden.
name: Casino Salzburg

detail_description: Nestled in a picturesque location next to a water mill, Stiftsbäckerei St Peter is the oldest bakery in Salzburg, dating back to the 12th century. Run by Franz Grabmer, a skilled master miller and baker, this rustic bakery offers an array of traditional breads baked in a wood-fired oven using natural sourdough. During Christmas season, they also craft handmade Kletzenbrot.
name: Stiftsbäckerei St Peter

excerpt: Established in 1621, this sprawling brewery & tavern offers indoor & outdoor seating.
detail_description: Augustiner Bräu Mülln is a historic brewery and tavern that has been in operation since 1621, making it one of the oldest establishments of its kind. The venue offers both indoor and outdoor seating, including a large beer garden. It is renowned for serving traditional Austrian cuisine, with options ranging from freshly baked pretzels to sausages with mustard, roast chicken with dumplings, deep-fried trout, and an assortment of cheeses.
name: Augustiner Bräu Mülln

excerpt: Historic 1893 building converted into an auditorium & stage for classic marionette productions.
detail_description: The Salzburger Marionettentheater is housed in a historic 1893 building that has been transformed into an auditorium and stage for classic marionette productions. The theater, a UNESCO World Heritage-listed site, boasts an opulent setting with stucco ornamentation and chandeliers. The attention to detail in costumes and backdrops is remarkable, and the skilled puppeteers bring wooden puppets to life with their expertise.
name: Salzburger Marionettentheater

excerpt: Alpine destination with skiing, hiking & biking routes, plus hotels, restaurants & a playground.
detail_description: Gaisberg, located in the eastern area of Salzburg, is an alpine destination offering a range of outdoor activities such as skiing, hiking, and mountain biking. Accessible by car or bus from Mirabell Palace, it's perfect for adventurous journeys and trekking. With over 20 kilometers of well-marked trails of varying difficulty levels and activities like paragliding and mountain biking available, Gaisberg is a dream for outdoor enthusiasts.
name: Gaisberg

excerpt: Franciscan church with architectural details (including a Baroque interior) from several periods.
detail_description: The Franziskanerkirche, also known as the Franciscan Church, is a historical landmark in Salzburg with architectural details from various periods. Dating back to the 8th century AD, this church showcases a blend of Romanesque, Gothic, and Baroque styles. Visitors can admire its stone carvings, soaring ceilings, graceful arches, stained glass windows, and intricately crafted high altar.
name: Franziskanerkirche

detail_description: The Salzburg Festival Ticketing offers visitors the chance to enjoy live concerts and shows at the Grosses Festspielhaus, one of the many theaters in Altstadt. With a stage over 100 meters wide, it hosts classical music acts such as the Symphony Orchestra Philharmonic. During the festival, pre-booked concert tickets are recommended for a leisurely visit. The ticketing service is known for its friendly and fast assistance in answering questions and providing additional information.
name: Salzburg Festival Ticketing

detail_description: Grünmarkt is a classic market located in Salzburg's old town, offering a variety of local products from the region. Visitors can find beautiful flowers, fresh fruits and vegetables, as well as organic bread. The market also features its own organic area on Saturdays with various vendors including bakers, butchers, cheese makers and more. Despite being crowded at times, the friendly and helpful sellers make it a pleasant experience for both city dwellers and tourists.
name: Grünmarkt

excerpt: Early 16th-century cemetery where royals, dignitaries & a few Mozart family members are buried.
detail_description: Friedhof Salzburg (St. Sebastian) is a serene 16th-century cemetery located near the St. Sebastian Church in Linzer Gasse 41. It serves as the final resting place for royals, dignitaries, and several members of the Mozart family, including Wolf Dietrich von Raitenau and Paracelsus. The cemetery's peaceful atmosphere offers visitors a moment of tranquility amidst its historical significance.
name: St Sebastian's Cemetery

excerpt: Beer tasting & exhibits on brewing history, plus Austrian cuisine in a brewpub & restaurant.
detail_description: Stiegl-Brauwelt is a must-visit destination for beer enthusiasts in Salzburg. The brewery offers a multi-sensory exploration of the world of beer, featuring exhibits on brewing history and a modern brewhouse where visitors can witness the bottling process. Additionally, guests can indulge in Austrian cuisine at the brewpub and restaurant. Stiegl, a family-owned brewery since 1492, is renowned for its popular beers that are widely available throughout Austria.
name: Stiegl-Brauwelt

excerpt: Narrow medieval street, birthplace of the "Silent Night" poet & home to past & current brothels.
detail_description: Steingasse is a charming medieval street located on the opposite side of the Salzach River from the famous baroque Altstadt in Salzburg. This narrow lane was once a major north-south route between the city and Italy during the Middle Ages, evidenced by its polished cobbles from horse hooves and wagon wheels. It is also known as the birthplace of the poet of 'Silent Night' and has been home to past and current brothels.
name: Steingasse

excerpt: Church designed by Baroque architect Johann Fischer von Erlach, known for its pristine white decor.
detail_description: Kollegienkirche, also known as the Collegiate Church, is a remarkable example of Baroque architecture in Salzburg. Designed by the renowned architect Johann Bernhard Fischer von Erlach, this church boasts an ornate facade and stunning interiors characterized by a pristine white decor that creates a striking play of light and shadow.
name: Kollegienkirche

detail_description: The Residenzbrunnen, also known as the Residenz Fountain, is a must-see attraction located in the lively Residenzplatz square in Salzburg. Designed by Italian sculptor Tommaso di Garone in 1661, this baroque masterpiece is considered one of the finest fountains in Austria. Its visually striking central marble column is adorned with statues representing various mythological figures.
name: Residenzbrunnen

detail_description: Café Glockenspiel is a historic café located in the heart of Salzburg, offering a charming outdoor dining area with stunning views of Mozartplatz and Fortress Hohensalzburg. Originally built as horse stables in the 17th and 18th century, it was transformed into an ice-cream parlor before becoming a café in 1925. The café's menu features homemade ice cream, delectable pastries, and a variety of meals.
name: Café Glockenspiel

detail_description: Sphaera, a striking golden globe topped with a man, has become an unofficial landmark in Salzburg. Positioned at Kapitelplatz since 2007, it's a popular spot for photos, especially when the area is less crowded. Located near the cathedral and beneath the fortress, Sphaera is one of Salzburg's most iconic modern art pieces alongside the pickles.
name: Goldene Kugel Kunstprojekt "Sphaera" von Stephan Balkenhol

excerpt: A robust collection of regional costumes, furniture, art & music in a historic home with views.
detail_description: The Folklore Museum is a treasure trove of regional culture, featuring an array of exhibits including costumes, furniture, art, and music in a historic setting with picturesque views. The museum's themed floors offer an interesting and unusual experience for visitors, complemented by friendly staff and lovingly designed rooms. Despite its small size, the museum boasts a tasteful collection of folk art, providing insight into daily life through icons, costumes, and decorated objects.
name: Folklore Museum

detail_description: M32, named after its postcode, is a cafe located on top of one of the largest hills in Salzburg, offering a fantastic view. Accessible by an elevator lift up the Monchsberg or via footpaths from the historic district, it also provides access to a modern art museum. The interior boasts a loft-like design with a mix of neon lighting and deer antlers.
name: M32

excerpt: Woodsy, old-world inn known for fried chicken, bread dumplings & beer, plus an outdoor terrace.
detail_description: Bärenwirt is a traditional Austrian inn located in Salzburg City, dedicated to preserving the iconic culture and cuisine of the region. The restaurant is renowned for its fried chicken, which is considered the best in Austria, as well as other classics like Salzburger Nockerl. The cozy tavern offers a warm, woody atmosphere reminiscent of a hunting lodge and has been serving traditional dishes since 1663.
name: Bärenwirt

detail_description: Café Tomaselli is a delightful gem nestled in the heart of Salzburg's old town, steeped in rich history since its establishment in 1703. This iconic coffeehouse beautifully embodies Austria's café culture, where delectable food and warm company are cherished equally. As you step inside, you're greeted by an enchanting atmosphere featuring dark-wood paneling, elegant marble tables, and vintage decor adorned with crystal chandeliers and baroque paintings.
name: Café Tomaselli

excerpt: Creative dishes & drinks are served in the elegant ambience of reputedly Europe's oldest restaurant.
detail_description: St. Peter Stiftskulinarium is a renowned restaurant that boasts being one of the oldest in Europe, with historical records dating back to 803 A.D. It was established by Benedictine monks and is steeped in history, with tales of famous figures such as Charlemagne and Columbus having dined or drank there. The restaurant offers an elegant ambiance and serves creative dishes and drinks, blending traditional Austrian standards with international specialties.
name: St. Peter Stiftskulinarium

detail_description: In Salzburg, the Alter Markt is a historic square surrounded by pastel-colored baroque townhouses and the St. Florian Fountain at its center. Once a bustling venue for markets and events, it now features attractions like the oldest coffee house in Salzburg, Cafe Tomaselli, and the renowned chocolatier Cafe-Konditorei Furst. The area also boasts traditional shops offering fine spices, fabrics, lace, handmade umbrellas, and exquisite local delicacies.
name: Alter Markt

excerpt: Striking contemporary clifftop museum in marble & glass, home to 20th- & 21st-century visual art.
detail_description: Perched on the cliffs of Monchsberg, the Museum der Moderne is a striking contemporary museum made of marble and glass. Founded in 1983 as the Rupertinum, it now houses a permanent collection focusing primarily on European artists from the 20th and 21st centuries.
name: Museum der Moderne
